Lesson 3: ある, いる

Both ある and いる mean "There is/There are". ある is used for non-living things, while いる is used for living things. 
(Both ある and いる are る/Ichidan verb)

Example:
X が あります
The particle が introduces, or presents, the item X. You can use あります when you want to say that these is something at a certain location. 
Example: 
テレビがありません

Note that あります is different from other verbs in three ways:
1) It calls for the particle に rather than で for the place description
2) The place description comes at the beginning of the sentence
3) The thing being described uses the particle が rather than は
Example:
あそこに銀行があります
（銀行／ぎんこう　- Bank）

You can also use あります to say that you "have" or "own" something. 
Example:
時間がありますか？
(時間／じかん - Time)

You also use あります when you want to say that an event will take place. 
Example:
火曜日にテストがあります
(火曜日／かようび　- Tuesday)

When you want to present a person, or a sentient being, rather than a thing, you need to use います。
Example:
あそこに学生がいます
(学生／がくせい - Student)

You can also use います to say that you have friends, siblings, and so on. 
Example:
日本語の友達がいます
(友達／ともだち　- Friend)
